                    <span style="font-size: 0.75rem; font-weight: normal; color: #6b7280; margin-left: auto;">Why decentralization hasn't worked</span>
                </h3>
                <p style="color: #4b5563; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-style: italic;">The 74th CAA's failure isn't accidental ‚Äî it serves powerful interests. Understanding these dynamics reveals why constitutional provisions remain on paper.</p>
                <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-6 mb-6">
                    <div class="mb-4">
                        <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">1. State Control Preservation</h4>
                        <ul class="text-sm">
                            <li><strong>Deliberate election delay:</strong> States control delimitation to prevent SEC from holding elections; Telangana SEC had to go to High Court to compel state action <a href="resources.html#ref-cse-waste-to-worth-2024" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[141]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Parastatal preference:</strong> Creating parallel bodies (UDAs, Water Corps) keeps power with state, not ULBs <a href="resources.html#ref-cse-waste-to-worth-2024" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[141,142]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Overriding powers retained:</strong> States maintain power to approve ULB budgets, plans, bye-laws despite constitutional devolution <a href="resources.html#ref-indiaspend-sewage-treatment-rehaul-2024" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[142]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Leverage:</strong> Autonomous State Election Commissions; transfer delimitation power per 2nd ARC recommendation</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="mb-4">
                        <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">2. Fiscal Dependency Trap</h4>
                        <ul class="text-sm">
                            <li><strong>Designed weakness:</strong> No constitutional provision for municipal revenue base ‚Äî states control all tax authority, rates, grants <a href="resources.html#ref-cse-waste-to-worth-2024" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[141]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>SFC delays:</strong> 6th SFC was due in 2019, 5th SFC recommendations still being implemented; delays of 49-903 days in constitution <a href="resources.html#ref-indiaspend-sewage-treatment-rehaul-2024" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[142]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Unpredictable transfers:</strong> ULBs can't plan when grants are discretionary and delayed; ‚Çπ196 Cr shortfall in Odisha alone <a href="resources.html#ref-indiaspend-sewage-treatment-rehaul-2024" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[142]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Leverage:</strong> Central Valuation Boards for property tax; predictable grant formulas; own revenue autonomy</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="mb-4">
                        <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">3. Capacity Starvation</h4>
                        <ul class="text-sm">
                            <li><strong>Controlled recruitment:</strong> State governments control staff assessment, recruitment, pay, transfers, disciplinary action ‚Äî not ULBs <a href="resources.html#ref-indiaspend-sewage-treatment-rehaul-2024" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[142]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Declining strength:</strong> Sanctioned staff decreased despite population growth; 35-65% vacancies across cities <a href="resources.html#ref-cse-waste-to-worth-2024" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[141,143]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Skill mismatch:</strong> First-time councillors unaware of municipal systems; commissioners lack urban governance experience <a href="resources.html#ref-cse-waste-to-worth-2024" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[141]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Leverage:</strong> Municipal cadre establishment; mandatory induction training; stable commissioner tenures</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="mb-4">
                        <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">4. Ward Committee Theater</h4>
                        <ul class="text-sm">
                            <li><strong>Mandated but meaningless:</strong> Constitutional requirement exists but most states haven't notified implementation rules <a href="resources.html#ref-sandrp-non-functional-stp-2025" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[143]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Political capture:</strong> Where formed, nominations are politically motivated; citizen participation absent <a href="resources.html#ref-cse-waste-to-worth-2024" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[141]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>No power:</strong> Advisory role only, no budget authority, no staff ‚Äî "bridge to nowhere" <a href="resources.html#ref-indiaspend-sewage-treatment-rehaul-2024" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[142]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Leverage:</strong> Kerala/Gujarat models with functional ward committees; mandatory Area Sabha at sub-ward level</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="mb-4">
                        <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">5. Councillor Devaluation</h4>
                        <ul class="text-sm">
                            <li><strong>Pay disparity:</strong> Councillors earn ‚Çπ2,500-25,000/month vs MLAs ‚Çπ50,000-1,83,000 ‚Äî 10-50x gap <a href="resources.html#ref-sandrp-non-functional-stp-2025" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[143]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Term mismatch:</strong> Mayor tenure 1-2.5 years in many states vs Panchayat presidents 5 years <a href="resources.html#ref-sandrp-non-functional-stp-2025" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[143]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Indirect election:</strong> Most mayors indirectly elected; less accountable than directly elected counterparts <a href="resources.html#ref-sandrp-non-functional-stp-2025" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[143]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Leverage:</strong> Five-year mayoral terms; direct mayoral election; councillor pay parity with MLAs</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="mb-4">
                        <h4 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">6. Small Town Neglect</h4>
                        <ul class="text-sm">
                            <li><strong>Big city bias:</strong> JNNURM covered only 65 cities; small/medium towns can't access external funds <a href="resources.html#ref-cse-waste-to-worth-2024" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[141]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Capacity cliff:</strong> Small towns can't prepare project reports to qualify for grants; 80% own revenue from Municipal Corporations only <a href="resources.html#ref-cse-waste-to-worth-2024" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[141]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Population-blind staffing:</strong> Same population criterion regardless of area, complexity, growth rate <a href="resources.html#ref-indiaspend-sewage-treatment-rehaul-2024" style="font-size: 0.7rem;">[142]</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Leverage:</strong> Differentiated support for small towns; regional capacity building centers; simplified funding access</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

